      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Color QuickDraw expects that the sizes of all components are the same, and that the value of the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "cmpCount",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " field multiplied by the value of the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "cmpSize",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " field is less than or equal to the value in the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "pixelSize",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " field.For an indexed pixel value, which has only one component, the value of the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "cmpSize",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " field is the same as the value of the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "pixelSize",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " field; that is, 1, 2, 4, or 8. For direct pixels there are two additional possibilities. A 16-bit pixel, which has three components, has a ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "cmpSize",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " value of 5; this leaves an unused high-order bit, which Color QuickDraw sets to 0. A 32-bit pixel, which has three components (red, green, and blue), has a ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "cmpSize",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " value of 8; this leaves an unused high-order byte, which Color QuickDraw sets to 0.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "If presented with a 32-bit image (for example, in the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "CopyBits",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " procedure) Color QuickDraw passes whatever bits are there, and it does not set the high byte to 0. Generally, therefore, your application should clear the memory for the image to 0 before creating a 16-bit or 32-bit image.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
  ],
